Melchior Lorck,; v. 3; Kayser. W. Hamburger Turcica des 16. Jahrhunderts. (Philobiblon Jahrg. 19, Heft 1 (1975): p. 4-53),; 31; Prange, C. Die Zeitungen undZeitschriften des 17. Jahrhunderts in Hamburg und Altona,; p. 177-202SUBJECT(S)Descriptor:             Austro-Turkish War, 1683-1699 -- Periodicals -- Early works to 1800.Costume -- Turkey -- Periodicals -- Early works to 1800.Austro-Turkish War, 1683-1699 -- Periodicals -- Early works to 1800.Guerre austro-turque, 1683-1699 -- Périodiques -- Ouvrages avant 1800.Costume.Genre/Form:             Broadsides.Woodcuts.Early works.History.Periodicals.Pictorial works.Time:                   1683-1699Geographic:             Vienna (Austria) -- History -- Siege, 1683 -- Periodicals -- Early works to 1800.Turkey -- Pictorial works -- Early works to 1800.Asie Mineure -- Ouvrages illustrés -- Ouvrages avant 1800.Austria -- Vienna.Turkey.Note(s):                Most issues consist of a single half-sheet printed on both sides. On recto of most issues is a single illustration (subjects chiefly Turkish) with descriptive text; textcontinued on verso. On verso at bottom are dated reports from various cities on the ongoing events of the Austro-Turkish War, including the 1683 siege of Vienna; in two columns. Final issue is [4] p.(fol.), with double-spread illustration on p. [2-3]./ Title from caption./ Alternative title, appearing on first issue only, supplied from facsimile of a copy of [N 1] held by the Royal Library,Copenhagen, in Fischer, v. 3, p. 10./ Editor: Eberhard Werner Happel./ All illustrations by Melchior Lorichs except those for N 39, 65, 67-68, 107-108, 110, 132-133. The Lorichs illustrations wereprinted from woodblocks fabricated 1565-1583. See Fischer, v. 3, 282-286. Woodcuts for N 132 and 133 signed: H. v. W.; Kayser identifies the artist as H. von Wiering. Woodcuts for N 107-108 and 110,all unsigned, are by L. Danet according to Kayser. Kayser states woodcuts for N 39, 65, and 67, 80 are by unknown artists but Fischer counts the woodcut for N 80 among those by Lorichs. Kayser stateswoodcut for N 68 is by Lorichs; according to Fischer it is not./ For a discussion of E.W. Happel's use of texts by M. Lorichs in the descriptions of the illustrations, see Fischer, v. 3, p. 18-20 andrelevant catalog entries in same. According to Kayser the reports on ongoing events of the war were taken from T. von Wiering's Relations-Courier. For a discussion of T. von Wiering's newspapers andhis collaboration with Happel, see Prange./ The Lorichs illustrations (with signatures and dates removed) repeat 123 of 128 woodcuts previously issued with different set titles in Hamburg in 1626 and1646. See Fischer, v. 3, p. 7-11, and the relevant catalog entries in same./ Later issued as part of a collected work: Der Türckische Schau-Platz eröfnet und fürgestelt in sehr vielen nach demLeben gezeichneten Figuren. Hamburg : Thomas von Wiering, 1685./ Most issues lack imprint. Kayser identifies printer/publisher ("Drucker-Verleger") as Thomas von Wiering/ Decorative initials./ GettyResearch Institute's copies of N 4 and N 6 lack the distribution statements cited in Kayser, p. 46 ("Werden verkaufft in Hamburg in guelden A.B.C." and "Werden verkaufft bey der Boerse in gueldenA.B.C."). Getty Research Institute's copy of N 18 has distribution statement on verso, not noted in Kayser: Zubeommen [i.e. Zu bekommen] im Gülden A.B.C. Kayser cites first word of title of N 2 as:Tuerckis [i.e. Türckis]; Getty Research Intstitute's copy of N 2 has: Türck.Other Titles:           Türckischer Estaats- und Krieges- Bericht; Kurtze und gründliche Beschreibung des türckischen Käysers, Grosz- und anderer Veziers, Militz, Land und Leuten,Gewonheiten, Krieges- und Lebens-Arth, Gewehr, Kleydung, and was davon ferner zu berichten nötig; Some issues have title:; Türck. Estats- und Krieges- Bericht; Some issues have title:; Türckis.Estats- und Krieges- Bericht; N 133 (11 Decemb. 1684) has title:; Türck. Estats- und Kreisge- [sic] Bericht; N 135-137 have title:; Turck. Jahrhunderts ;; Nr. 6478.Note(s):                  Styled "Wochenschrifft vor frauenzimmer" in the privilege of the elector of Saxony, prefixed to v.5 ("Wochenschrift" in the bibliographies of Heinsius and Kayser;"Vierteljahrschrift für frauenzimmer" in Góedeke's Grundriss); in Jacobi's "Vorrede," prefixed to v.8, it is called "Monathschrift." Three "Stücke," each preceded by half-title, form a volume(in v.8 only the first and third "stück" have half-title); the names of the month appear on half-titles of vols. 1-5. Vols. 1-4 appeared from October, 1774, to September, 1775; vols. 5-8 (pub. byHaude & Spener) from "Jenner" to [December?] 1776. The title page, and the half-titles of 1st and 3d "stück" in v. 8 have date l766; the publishers' "Nachricht" at end of v.8 is dated May 1778.Vols. 5-8 are paged continuously, 961 (i.e. 955 p.), [3] p., nos. 484-in v. 7, 885-8 in v. 8 being omitted. The continuation of the periodical under a new editorship, announced by the publishers atend of v.8, seems never to have appeared. "Iris. ein taschenbuch für 1803[-1813 ̈Hrsg. von G.J. Jacobi" was pub. by Orell, Füssli und compagnie in Zürich./ Edited by J.G. Jacobi; withcontributions by the editor, Goethe, Heinse, F.H.
